cs.SY, cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.CR, cs.DC 

The paper deals with a remote state estimation scenario involving multiple sensors transmitting data through a shared channel. This suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. The paper also discusses time synchronization attacks and countermeasures, which could fall under the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. The use of linear dynamical processes and estimation error covariance could indicate a connection to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The paper also involves scheduling and transmission policies, which could relate to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category. Finally, the use of algorithms and simulation examples could suggest a connection to the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category.
